-content">
        <p>Understanding what statistical significance is and why it matter=
s is key for getting the most out of your CRO efforts=E2=80=94but diving in=
to the deep end of statistical analysis can quickly become overwhelming.</p=
>
<p>To help you better understand the role of statistical significance, prob=
ability, and how it all relates to your marketing tactics, we=E2=80=99ve pu=
t together this article.</p>
<p>You=E2=80=99ll learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>What statistical significance is</li>
<li>Why it matters for your <a href=3D"https://unbounce.com/product/ab-test=
ing-tool/">A/B tests</a></li>
<li>How to calculate statistical significance</li>
<li>Examples and ideas to help you get started</li>
</ul>
<h2 class=3D"position-relative">What is statistical significance?<a name=3D=
"What-is-statistical-" class=3D"blog-toc-link"></a></h2>
<p>In simple terms, statistical significance means that a test=E2=80=99s re=
sults are unlikely to be the result of chance or random occurrence.</p>
<p>Basically, your testing efforts have found a genuine, observable result=
=E2=80=94even if it isn=E2=80=99t the result you were hoping for. If we wan=
ted to get more technical, though, then statistical significance is a measu=
re of the probability that your test=E2=80=99s null hypothesis is true.</p>
<p><i>=E2=80=9CHang on, though, what=E2=80=99s a null hypothesis?=E2=80=9D<=
/i></p>
<p>A <strong>null hypothesis</strong> is a sort of counter-hypothesis desig=
ned to keep your tests as objective as possible. A null hypothesis doesn=E2=
=80=99t require as much careful thought as your test=E2=80=99s hypothesis=
=E2=80=94it simply says that your test=E2=80=99s results are not correlated=
 to your activities until you can actually prove it.</p>
<p>In other words, a null hypothesis says that a test=E2=80=99s results are=
 caused by pure, random chance.</p>
<p>Still with us?</p>
<p>We get it=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s a ton of new terminology and jargon to =
wrap your head around. If you=E2=80=99re still scratching your head about i=
t, it might help to contextualize statistical significance and its related =
terms in a familiar CRO setting.</p>
<p><strong>Here=E2=80=99s a simple example:</strong></p>
<p>Imagine you=E2=80=99re running an A/B test with two landing page variant=
s.</p>
<p>Your hypothesis for your test is this:</p>
<p><i>=E2=80=9CBy changing the headline on my hero variant, I predict we=E2=
=80=99ll see a 5% increase in the page=E2=80=99s conversion rate, compared =
to the control variant.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</i></p>
<p>For this example, your null hypothesis could be something as simple as t=
his:</p>
<p><i>=E2=80=9CThe changes made to the hero variant won=E2=80=99t have a me=
asurable effect on the conversion rate, so any results we see can be attrib=
uted to random chance.=E2=80=9D</i></p>
<p>As ridiculous as it might seem to say out loud or even put into words, a=
 null hypothesis is nonetheless a necessary guardrail when you=E2=80=99re t=
rying to determine statistical significance=E2=80=94even if you don=E2=80=
=99t believe what you=E2=80=99re saying.</p>
      </div>
