<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">What is p-value in statistical significance?=
</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><em>Statistical significance</em> and <em>null hypothesis</em> aren=E2=
=80=99t the only important terms you need to know. If you=E2=80=99ve skimme=
d anything about these topics, then you=E2=80=99ve probably also seen some =
mention of =E2=80=9Cp-value.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>P-value is simply a way of expressing statistical significance, =
and may also be referred to as a =E2=80=9Cconfidence interval.=E2=80=9D</st=
rong></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Formally, p-value is a <a href=3D"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/p=
-value.asp">statistical measurement used to validate a hypothesis against o=
bserved data</a>, and it helps determine the probability that observed find=
ings are the result of random chance. Generally:&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list"><div class=3D"container single-2023-right-conte=
nt text-left">
<li>The higher a p-value, the more likely it is that your results are due t=
o chance.</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>The lower a p-value, the more confident you can be that your results ar=
e statistically significant.</li>
</div></ul>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>While the exact figure may vary, it=E2=80=99s recommended that most test=
s aim for a p-value of 5% or less to increase confidence that your data is =
reliable.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading position-relative">Why is it important for yo=
ur A/B tests to be statistically significant?<a name=3D"Why-is-it-important=
-" class=3D"blog-toc-link"></a></h2>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>So now we=E2=80=99re getting into the meat and potatoes: Why is it impor=
tant that your A/B tests be statistically significant?&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>There are four major reasons why you would want your tests to be statist=
ically significant:</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<ol class=3D"wp-block-list"><div class=3D"container single-2023-right-conte=
nt text-left">
<li>To validate your hypothesis</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>To ensure informed decision-making</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>To reduce uncertainty</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>To help you uncover further findings</li>
</div></ol>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Let=E2=80=99s take a closer look at each of these reasons.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Validating hypotheses</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>The most apparent reason for ensuring statistical significance is that i=
t helps you validate the hypothesis you=E2=80=99re testing. Whether that hy=
pothesis is correct or not is less important; statistical significance simp=
ly means the tests and data you=E2=80=99re gathering are valid and worth an=
alyzing.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Informing decision making</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Statistically significant data helps you make a strong basis for any dec=
ision making you undertake. Because you know that your data is reliable, yo=
u can be more confident in using it to guide and shape your strategy.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Reducing uncertainty</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>This one is closely related to your decision-making efforts, but bears r=
epeating here=E2=80=94by determining your data is statistically significant=
, you=E2=80=99re reducing uncertainty and ambiguity in your testing and CRO=
 processes. Having a strong foundation of good, reliable data is critical, =
as it gives you precedents you can point to and something you can rely on t=
o explain your reasoning and put any doubts to rest.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Guiding further findings</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Finally, statistically significant data is vital for helping you figure =
out next steps. This is a foundational part of your CRO efforts=E2=80=94we=
=E2=80=99ve written before about how even those <a href=3D"https://unbounce=
.com/landing-page-articles/what-is-ab-testing/#:~:text=3DEven%20a%20failed%=
20test%20will%20give%20you%20more%20context">A/B tests that don=E2=80=99t c=
onfirm your hypothesis shouldn=E2=80=99t be considered failures</a>.&nbsp;<=
/p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>As long as you=E2=80=99re still gathering statistically significant data=
, you can learn from it and use it to formulate new hypotheses and discover=
 new information.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading position-relative">How to calculate statistic=
al significance<a name=3D"How-to-calculate-sta" class=3D"blog-toc-link"></a=
></h2>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Now that we=E2=80=99ve covered all the background details and the reason=
s why statistical significance is important, let=E2=80=99s dig into how you=
 can go about calculating statistical significance in your next CRO experim=
ent=E2=80=99s findings.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Calculating statistical significance can be an extensive process if you=
=E2=80=99re just running the numbers by hand=E2=80=94thankfully, tools like=
 <a href=3D"https://unbounce.com/product/ab-testing-tool/">Unbounce=E2=80=
=99s A/B testing</a> tool help automate these processes so you=E2=80=99re n=
ot crunching the numbers yourself. But knowing how to make the calculations=
 yourself and understanding exactly what you=E2=80=99re calculating can hel=
p you develop a better understanding to inform further testing.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>Generally speaking, calculating statistical significance involve=
s:</strong></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<ol class=3D"wp-block-list"><div class=3D"container single-2023-right-conte=
nt text-left">
<li>Create a hypothesis</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>Determine the significance level</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>Calculate ideal sample size</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>Collect data</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>Analyze data</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>Interpret results</li>
</div></ol>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">1. Create a hypothesis&nbsp;</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>No matter what test you=E2=80=99re running, you=E2=80=99re going to need=
 a hypothesis and a null hypothesis. Your hypothesis is just the <a href=3D=
"https://unbounce.com/a-b-testing/how-to-formulate-an-a-b-test-hypothesis/"=
>typical sort of hypothesis</a> you=E2=80=99d typically develop for any CRO=
 experiment you run=E2=80=94and you probably already have some idea about w=
hat you=E2=80=99re looking to accomplish.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>To get a bit more technical, your hypothesis should specifically be a cl=
ear statement that predicts a potential outcome following a change to a sin=
gle variable, <a href=3D"https://unbounce.com/landing-page-articles/what-is=
-ab-testing/">like we=E2=80=99ve written about before</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>And remember, for A/B testing, you=E2=80=99re only changing <em>one vari=
able at a time</em>.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Alongside your standard hypothesis, you=E2=80=99ll need a null hypothesi=
s to help with your calculations. Like we mentioned earlier, your null hypo=
thesis simply says there=E2=80=99s no significant difference between groups=
 you=E2=80=99re comparing.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">2. Determine a significance level</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Next, you=E2=80=99ve got to determine the significance level. The signif=
icance level is a sort of threshold for the strength of evidence in your A/=
B test that must be gathered before you can reject your null hypothesis.</p=
>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Basically, it=E2=80=99s the level of probability or risk that your resul=
ts are due to chance=E2=80=94the other side of your test=E2=80=99s p-value.=
 The significance level is sometimes referred to as the alpha.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>In most cases, you=E2=80=99ll determine a significance level between 0.0=
1 or 0.05, or 1-5%. This is a pretty common range for most significance lev=
els. Remember, the lower the significance level, the stronger your evidence=
 needs to be.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">3. Calculate ideal sample size</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>As part of your efforts to determine statistical significance, you need =
to ensure you have the right sample size.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>This can be a tricky process. Your best bet for figuring out the ideal s=
ample size for your test is using <a href=3D"https://unbounce.com/ab-test-d=
uration-calculator/">Unbounce=E2=80=99s A/B Test Duration and Sample Size c=
alculator</a>=E2=80=94this will let you quickly punch in your goals and get=
 useful target numbers to determine how long your test should run and how l=
arge your audience should be.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"1999" height=3D"1440" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://w=
ww.w3.org/2000/svg'%20width=3D'1999'%20height=3D'1440'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%2=
01999%201440'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-141065 perfmatters-l=
azy" data-src=3D"https://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-significance-calcu=
lator.png" data-srcset=3D"https://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-significa=
nce-calculator.png 1999w, https://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-significa=
nce-calculator-150x108.png 150w, https://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-si=
gnificance-calculator-347x250.png 347w, https://unbounce.com/photos/statist=
ical-significance-calculator-80x58.png 80w, https://unbounce.com/photos/sta=
tistical-significance-calculator-768x553.png 768w, https://unbounce.com/pho=
tos/statistical-significance-calculator-1536x1106.png 1536w, https://unboun=
ce.com/photos/statistical-significance-calculator-1000x720.png 1000w, https=
://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-significance-calculator-650x468.png 650w=
, https://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-significance-calculator-300x216.p=
ng 300w, https://unbounce.com/photos/statistical-significance-calculator-16=
0x115.png 160w" data-sizes=3D"(max-width: 1999px) 100vw, 1999px"></figure>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>There are a number of variables involved in calculating sample size, so =
using a calculator is the easiest way to streamline what can otherwise be a=
 convoluted process.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>This is also a great opportunity to determine standard deviation (how va=
ried the data is above the mean or expected data) and standard error (the s=
tandard deviation of the sample population).&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Here=E2=80=99s the formula for calculating standard deviation:&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>Standard deviation =3D =E2=88=9A((=E2=88=91|x=E2=88=92=CE=BC|^ 2=
) / (N-1))</strong></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list"><div class=3D"container single-2023-right-conte=
nt text-left">
<li>=E2=88=9A indicates we=E2=80=99re taking the square root</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>=CE=A3 represents the sum of the data</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>x represents individual data</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>=CE=BC represents the data=E2=80=99s mean for each group</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>N represents the total sample</li>
</div></ul>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>And the formula for calculating standard error:</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>Standard error =3D =E2=88=9A((s1/N1) (s2/N2))</strong></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>In this equation, the variables are as follows:</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list"><div class=3D"container single-2023-right-conte=
nt text-left">
<li>=E2=88=9A indicates we=E2=80=99re taking the square root</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>s1 represents the standard deviation of your first group</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>N1 represents group one=E2=80=99s sample size</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>s2 represents the standard deviation of your second group</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>N2 represents group two=E2=80=99s sample size</li>
</div></ul>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">4. Collect data</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Next, you run your A/B test and gather your data. We=E2=80=99ve written =
a ton on the <a href=3D"https://unbounce.com/landing-page-articles/what-is-=
ab-testing/">ins and outs of A/B testing</a> elsewhere, so we won=E2=80=99t=
 go into too much detail here. Just make sure any analytics tools you=E2=80=
=99re running are set up properly and that you=E2=80=99re sending your audi=
ence to the appropriate variants.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Make sure you=E2=80=99re collecting data from a random sample to avoid a=
ny bias that could influence your test=E2=80=99s results. Let the test run =
and get your data in order.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">5. Analyze data</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>This is probably the most complex part of calculating statistical signif=
icance, and it=E2=80=99s going to be pretty heavy on the math.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>There are a few ways to run a statistical analysis of your data, includi=
ng:</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>1. </strong><a href=3D"https://www.scribbr.com/statistics/chi-sq=
uare-test-of-independence/"><strong>Chi-square tests</strong></a></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>This is a statistical test that can be used to determine if there is a s=
ignificant association between two categorical variables. These tests can h=
elp you see if the results you observe are different from what you=E2=80=99=
d expect by chance, as in your null hypothesis.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Chi-square tests are one of the most reliable ways to analyze your A/B t=
esting data. These are discrete tests that only generate a limited number o=
f results, which helps focus your testing efforts and lets you draw more ac=
curate conclusions.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>2. </strong><a href=3D"https://www.ncl.ac.uk/webtemplate/ask-ass=
ets/external/maths-resources/z-test.html"><strong>Z-tests</strong></a></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>These tests are used to determine if there=E2=80=99s a significant diffe=
rence between the means of two groups when the sample size is large and the=
 population variance is known. It=E2=80=99s often used for comparing propor=
tions or means.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>3. </strong><a href=3D"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/t-te=
st.asp"><strong>T-tests</strong></a></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>T-tests are similar to Z-tests, but are used when you=E2=80=99re dealing=
 with a small sample size or an unknown population variance. These tests co=
mpare the means of two different groups to see if there are any significant=
 differences.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>4. </strong><a href=3D"https://www.qualtrics.com/experience-mana=
gement/research/anova/#:~:text=3DANOVA%20is%20a%20versatile%20and,means%20o=
f%20your%20independent%20variable."><strong>Analysis of variance (ANOVA) te=
sts</strong></a></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>ANOVA tests are used to compare the means of three or more groups to fig=
ure out if at least one group=E2=80=99s mean is notably different from the =
others. These tests are helpful if you=E2=80=99re comparing multiple groups=
 at the same time, like in a multivariate test or A/B/n test (where the =E2=
=80=98n=E2=80=99 just means more than two variants).&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">6. Interpret results</h3>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Finally, you can interpret your data. This is the meat and potatoes of a=
ny A/B test, where you put your findings under the microscope and figure ou=
t what it=E2=80=99s trying to tell you.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>If your results come back within that threshold, congratulations! Your t=
est results are statistically significant and you can now start to use them=
 to determine what actions you want to take on your landing pages.&nbsp;</p=
>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>You=E2=80=99ll also need to calculate the p-value. This is most often do=
ne via statistical software or referring to probability tables, and it=E2=
=80=99s important to remember that how you calculate your p-value will depe=
nd on the type of test you=E2=80=99ve run in the first place.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Once you have your p-value, you need to compare it to your previously es=
tablished significance level.</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Remember how we mentioned that, for most tests, you=E2=80=99d set your s=
ignificance level between 0.01 and 0.05? If your p-value sits within that t=
hreshold of 1 to 5%, then you can safely assume your results are statistica=
lly significant.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>But if your p-value is above the threshold you=E2=80=99ve set, then you =
can=E2=80=99t be certain your tests are generating reliable, valid data=E2=
=80=94which means you may need to run the test again or revise your testing=
 parameters.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading position-relative">Statistical significance e=
xample<a name=3D"Statistical-signific" class=3D"blog-toc-link"></a></h2>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>So we=E2=80=99ve covered a ton of information here, and statistics can b=
e a bit daunting to try and tackle on your own. Here=E2=80=99s a simple exa=
mple to put things in perspective.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Say you=E2=80=99re testing two versions of a CTA button on your landing =
page. You=E2=80=99ve settled on =E2=80=9Cbuy now=E2=80=9D as your button te=
xt but you want to see what design elements will help you drive conversions=
.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>You make one variant page with a red button design (variant A) and one w=
ith a green button design (variant B). You A/B test your elements and get t=
he following results:</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list"><div class=3D"container single-2023-right-conte=
nt text-left">
<li>Variant A had 1,000 visitors and 100 of them converted=E2=80=94a 10% co=
nversion rate.</li>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<li>Variant B had 1,000 visitors, but 120 of them converted=E2=80=94a 12% c=
onversion rate.</li>
</div></ul>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>At first glance, you might think variant B is the clear winner and that =
you should be making similar updates across ALL your landing pages, right?<=
/p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p><strong>Not so fast.</strong></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>These results might not be statistically significant=E2=80=94so you star=
t analyzing the data more closely.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>You start by calculating the difference in conversion rates=E2=80=94easy=
, 2%. You need to compare this variance to the standard variation you=E2=80=
=99d expect when comparing two groups. You run your statistical test, and d=
etermine that the probability of seeing a 2% difference is very low, coming=
 in under 5%.&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<div class=3D"container single-2023-right-content text-left">
<p>Because this p-value is below the significance level for your test, you=
=E2=80=99re confident that the results you achieved aren=E2=80=99t simply a=
 stroke of good luck and that the green button on variant B is the cause of=
 the higher conversion rate.</p>
</div>

